The exact prevalence and disease associations of HCoV‐NL63 in children are now being studied at a number of institutions. Several recent studies that have examined respiratory specimens from children with respiratory illnesses of unknown etiology found prevalences of 2.1%–9.3% [5–7
, 13–17
]. Our data, which show a similar prevalence of 7.7%, further support the conclusions that HCoV‐NL63 was circulating in our community, was detectable by our methods, and was not more prevalent in patients with KS than in control subjects with upper‐respiratory‐tract infections that were not caused by 7 common respiratory viruses.
